#: src/glossary.md:3
msgid ""
"Plain-language definitions of the terms and acronyms used across this "
"documentation. It exists so a first-time or non-specialist reader can decode "
"the security and architecture jargon without leaving the page they are on."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:7
msgid "Product concepts"
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:9
msgid ""
"**AI Agent Assembly (AAASM)** : The product this hub documents: a governance "
"layer that sits between your AI agents and the outside world and enforces "
"policy, tracks cost, and intercepts unsafe actions before they run."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:14
msgid ""
"**Governance layer** : The one-line description of what AI Agent Assembly "
"_is_ — a control that evaluates and enforces what an agent is allowed to do, "
"rather than only observing what it did after the fact."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:19
msgid ""
"**Gateway (`aa-gateway`)** : The central service that holds the agent "
"registry, evaluates policy, and tracks per-team budgets. Every interception "
"layer reports to it."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:23
msgid ""
"**Agent** : An autonomous or semi-autonomous program that calls tools, "
"models, or network services on your behalf — the thing AI Agent Assembly "
"governs."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:27
msgid ""
"**Policy** : A set of allow / deny / audit rules that decide whether an "
"agent action is permitted. See the [Policy reference](policy-reference.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:31
msgid ""
"**Policy-as-code** : Expressing those rules as versioned YAML/JSON documents "
"that can be reviewed and deployed through normal Git workflows, instead of "
"clicking through a UI."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:35
msgid ""
"**Budget** : A per-team cap on token or dollar spend. When exceeded, the "
"gateway can deny further agent calls."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:39
msgid "Interception layers"
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:41
msgid ""
"**SDK layer** : In-process governance: the language SDK wraps your agent's "
"calls and applies allow/deny decisions before any request leaves the process."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:45
msgid ""
"**Sidecar proxy (`aa-proxy`)** : A companion process that intercepts an "
"agent's outbound HTTPS traffic to enforce policy without changing the "
"agent's code."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:49
msgid ""
"**eBPF sensor (`aa-ebpf`)** : A kernel-level sensor (Linux only) that "
"watches TLS libraries and process syscalls to catch actions — and bypass "
"attempts — that the layers above miss."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:53
msgid "Security & identity terms"
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:55
msgid ""
"**eBPF** (extended Berkeley Packet Filter) : A Linux kernel technology for "
"safely running small sandboxed programs inside the kernel to observe or "
"filter events, without modifying kernel source."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:59
msgid ""
"**uprobe** (user-space probe) : An eBPF hook attached to a function in a "
"user-space library (for example, an SSL library) so the sensor can observe "
"calls at that point."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:63
msgid ""
"**Sidecar** : A deployment pattern where a helper process runs alongside "
"your application and handles a cross-cutting concern (here, traffic "
"interception)."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:67
msgid ""
"**MitM** (man-in-the-middle) : Sitting in the path of a connection to "
"inspect or control it. The proxy performs _authorized_ MitM of an agent's "
"HTTPS using a per-host certificate authority so it can apply egress policy."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:72
msgid ""
"**mTLS** (mutual TLS) : TLS where **both** the client and the server present "
"certificates, so each side cryptographically verifies the other's identity."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:76
msgid ""
"**STRIDE** : A threat-modeling framework categorizing risks as Spoofing, "
"Tampering, Repudiation, Information disclosure, Denial of service, and "
"Elevation of privilege. Used in the [Security model](security-model.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:81
msgid ""
"**SCIM** (System for Cross-domain Identity Management) : A standard protocol "
"for automatically provisioning and de-provisioning users and groups from "
"your identity provider into an application."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:85
msgid ""
"**SSO / SAML 2.0 / OIDC** : Single sign-on and the two federation protocols "
"(SAML 2.0 and OpenID Connect) used to let operators log in with an "
"enterprise identity provider."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:89
msgid ""
"**Ed25519** : A modern public-key signature algorithm, used here to sign "
"agent identity tokens."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:93
msgid ""
"**AES-256-GCM** : A symmetric authenticated-encryption algorithm, used here "
"to encrypt stored secrets at rest."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:97
msgid ""
"**HMAC-SHA256** : A keyed hash used to sign audit-log entries and webhook "
"payloads so tampering is detectable."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:101
msgid ""
"**IronClaw five-layer defense** : The name for AI Agent Assembly's "
"defense-in-depth model — five security _layers_ (Boundary, Identity, Policy, "
"Vault, Telemetry). These are distinct from the three _interception points_ "
"(SDK, proxy, eBPF), which all live inside the Boundary layer. See the "
"[Security model](security-model.md)."
msgstr ""

#: src/glossary.md:107
msgid ""
"**Audit log** : The append-only record of every agent action (policy checks, "
"events, budget debits). The open-source build ships a _basic_ audit log; the "
"_tamper-evident signed_ audit log (HMAC-SHA256) is an Enterprise capability "
"— see [Open Core Boundary](open-core-boundary.md)."
msgstr ""

